   <standOff>
      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_694" type="description">
            <term id="misc_694-term">By far the greatest changes</term>
            <gloss id="misc_694-gloss" target="#misc_694-term">
               <p>This lecture was first given on Thursday, 25 April 1805 at 2pm, and repeated on Wednesday, 5 March 1806, 8pm and Wednesday, 25 May 1808, 8pm. It is published in Humphry Davy on Geology: the 1805 Lectures for the General Audience, ed. Robert Siegfried and Robert H. Dott, Jnr (University of Wisconsin Press, 1980), pp. 116-29.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_790" type="description">
            <term id="misc_790-term">Hamilton on Vesuvius</term>
            <gloss id="misc_790-gloss" target="#misc_790-term">
               <p>Sir William Hamilton published letters on the subject of Mount Vesuvius in Philosophical Transactions in 1767, 1768, 1780, 1786 and 1795 [Vols. 57, 58, 70,  76 and 85]. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_806" type="description">
            <term id="misc_806-term">Cinnamon</term>
            <gloss id="misc_806-gloss" target="#misc_806-term">
               <p>An aromatic spice derived from the inner bark of trees in the Cinnamomum genus.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_805" type="description">
            <term id="misc_805-term">Sassafras</term>
            <gloss id="misc_805-gloss" target="#misc_805-term">
               <p>A type of deciduous tree known for its aromatic properties. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_791" type="description">
            <term id="misc_791-term">Scoria</term>
            <gloss id="misc_791-gloss" target="#misc_791-term">
               <p>Scoria is a rock formed from volcanic lava which is ejected and cooled in the air. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_339" type="description">
            <term id="misc_339-term">Pitcoal</term>
            <gloss id="misc_339-gloss" target="#misc_339-term">
               <p>Coal mined from the earth - distinguished from charcoal.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
      </listAnnotation>
      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_844">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Thucydides</forename>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c. 460 BCE"/>
            <death when="c. 400 BCE"/>
            <note>An Athenian historian and general, his History of the Peloponnesian War recounts the fifth-century BCE war between Sparta and Athens until the year 411 BCE. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_951">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Jesus</forename>
               <surname>Christ</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c. 6-4 BC"/>
            <death when="AD 30 or 33"/>
            <note>The central figure of Christianity; a first-century Jewish preacher and religious leader.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_138">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Aristotle</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="384 BCE"/>
            <death when="322 BCE"/>
            <note>A pupil of Plato's whose philosophical idealism he came to reject, arguing instead for the primacy of observations of natural phenomena. He thus established the divide between theory and experiment in science that can still be detected today. Aristotle's writings became the main way the natural world was understood from the Middle Ages to the seventeenth century, especially in the universities.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_185">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Pliny</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="23 CE"/>
            <death when="79 CE"/>
            <note>The Elder. Roman army officer and author who wrote an encyclopedic Natural History. Died in the aftermath of the eruption of Vesuvius.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_448">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Diodorus</forename>
               <surname>Siculus</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="fl 1st century BCE"/>
            <note>Of Sicily was an ancient Greek historian. He is known for writing the monumental universal history Bibliotheca historica, in forty books, fifteen of which survive intact, between 60 and 30 BCE.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_510">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Strabo</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c. 64 BCE"/>
            <death when="c. 24 CE"/>
            <note>Greek geographer, philosopher, and historian who lived in Asia Minor during the transitional period of the Roman Republic into the Roman Empire.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_401">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Julius</forename>
               <surname>Caesar</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="100 BCE"/>
            <death when="44 BCE"/>
            <note>Roman general and dictator who first landed an army in Britain. Assassinated to prevent him gaining total power in Rome.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_699">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Hamilton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1730"/>
            <death when="1803"/>
            <note>English diplomat, politician, antiquarian, and vulcanologist who served as the Envoy Extraordinary to the Kingdom of Naples from 1764 to 1800. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_308">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Lazzaro</forename>
               <surname>Spallanzani</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1799"/>
            <death when="1729"/>
            <note>Italian priest, biologist and physiologist.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_820">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Scipione</forename>
               <surname>Breislak</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1826"/>
            <note>Italian geologist of Swedish parentage. The vast works for the refining of sulphur in the volcanic district of Solfatara, near Naples, were erected under his direction. Professor of physics at the University of Ragusa, and subsequently at the Collegio Nazereno in Rome. He witnessed an eruption of Vesuvius in 1794 and subsequntly wrote Voyage Physique et Lithologique dans la Campagnie (1801). </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_300">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Déodat Gratet de</forename>
               <surname>Dolomieu</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1750"/>
            <death when="1801"/>
            <note>French geologist. The rock, and region of the Alps, dolomite was named after him.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_271">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Alexander von</forename>
               <surname>Humboldt</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1769"/>
            <death when="1859"/>
            <note>German geographer, naturalist and explorer. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_596">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Uno von</forename>
               <surname>Troil</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1746"/>
            <death when="1803"/>
            <note>Swedish traveller and the archbishop of Uppsala. He travelled to Iceland with Joseph Banks.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_597">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Francesco</forename>
               <surname>Ferrara</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1767"/>
            <death when="1850"/>
            <note>Italian geologist, active mainly in Sicily, and known especially for his vulcanology studies. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1077">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Heneage</forename>
               <surname>Finch</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1628"/>
            <death when="1689"/>
            <note>Heneage Finch, 3rd Earl of Winchilsea (c. 1628 – 28 September 1689) was an English peer and diplomat who served as the English ambassador to the Ottoman Empire from 1660 to 1669. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1083">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Charles II</forename>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1630"/>
            <death when="1685"/>
            <note>King of Scotland 1649-1651. Became King of England, Scotland and Ireland in the 1660 Reformation until his death in 1685. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_811">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Nicolas</forename>
               <surname>Lemery</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1645"/>
            <death when="1715"/>
            <note>French chemist, born at Rouen. He was one of the first to develop theories on acid-base chemistry.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1084">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Robert</forename>
               <surname>Plot</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1640"/>
            <death when="1696"/>
            <note>Robert Plot was an English naturalist and antiquarian who was the first professor of chemistry at the University of Oxford and the first keeper of the Ashmolean Museum.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
      <listPlace>
         <place xml:id="place_184">
            <placeName>Mount Etna</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">37.751123181461516,  14.9934134370738</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Mount Etna, or simply Etna, is an active stratovolcano on the east coast of Sicily, Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1325">
            <placeName>Aeolian Islands</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">38.59547428189624,  14.8208999350594</geo>
            </location>
            <note>sometimes referred to as the Lipari Islands after their largest island, are a volcanic archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea north of Sicily</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_569">
            <placeName>Sicily</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">37.65574735341652, 13.9118221346888</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Sicily is the largest and most populous island in the Mediterranean Sea and one of the twenty regions of Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_407">
            <placeName>Pompeii</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.747249521286264, 14.4988069931492</geo>
            </location>
            <note>An ancient city located in what is now the comune of Pompei near Naples in the Campania region of Italy. Pompeii was buried in volcanic ash in the Eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 CE. </note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_714">
            <placeName>Herculaneum</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.806110960828086, 14.349098914097301</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Herculaneum was an ancient Roman town, located in the modern-day comune of Ercolano, Campania, Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_169">
            <placeName>Mount Vesuvius</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.82295082311693,  14.4286697656167</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Mount Vesuvius is a somma-stratovolcano located on the Gulf of Naples in Campania, Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_183">
            <placeName>phlegrean fields</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.82787675400991,  14.1413603671697</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A volcano/volcanic area near Naples, Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1168">
            <placeName>Campania</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.905648848210596, 14.9811949065611</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A region of Italy; most of it is in the south-western portion of the Italian peninsula (with the Tyrrhenian Sea to its west), but it also includes the small Phlegraean Islands and the island of Capri.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_408">
            <placeName>Lipari</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">38.49459902628964,  14.926674045458199</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A commune including six of seven islands of the Aeolian Islands located in the Tyrrhenian Sea off the northern coast of Sicily in southern Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_177">
            <placeName>Andes</placeName>
            <note>Mountain range in western South America.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1037">
            <placeName>Catania</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">37.505800,  15.083608999999999</geo>
            </location>
            <note>An ancient port city in Italy, on Sicily's east coast.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_751">
            <placeName>Hekla</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">63.99534619968239, -19.665621686038399</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Hekla is a volcano in Iceland. It has erupted many times in recorded history. 1766-68 was the eruption closest to Davy's time. </note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_237">
            <placeName>Iceland</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">65.03137079206361,  -18.761459110408101</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A Nordic island country between the North Atlantic and Arctic Oceans.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1041">
            <placeName>Torre del Greco</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.781417,  14.396506</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A comune in the Metropolitan City of Naples in Italy. Located at the foot of Mount Vesuvius, Torre del Greco was partly destroyed in an eruption of the volcano in 1631.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1042">
            <placeName>Resina</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.803236,  14.347239</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Now Ercolano, Resino was a medieval town built on the lava stream left by the eruption of Vesuvius (AD 79) that destroyed the ancient city of Herculaneum, from which the present name is derived.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_156">
            <placeName>Naples</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.85176026322066,  14.2037545535986</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Naples is the regional capital of Campania in Italy. It is located beneath the volcano, Vesuvius.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1043">
            <placeName>Ottaviano</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.850269,  14.476957000000001</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A comune in the Italian region of Campania, located about 20 kilometres east of Naples in the Vesuvian Area. </note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1360">
            <placeName>Ealand</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">53.59558623178524,  -0.81577099790990804</geo>
            </location>
            <note>English village in the county of Lincolnshire and the region of Yorkshire and the Humber. </note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_287">
            <placeName>Yorkshire</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">53.99003331206097, -1.07287393265237</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Yorkshire is a historic county in northern England and the largest by area size in the United Kingdom.</note>
         </place>
      </listPlace>
      <listAnnotation type="nonenglish">
         <note xml:id="nonenglish_356" type="description">
            <term id="nonenglish_356-term">περι ϑαυμαςιων ακματων</term>
            <gloss id="nonenglish_356-gloss" target="#nonenglish_356-term">
               <p>Concerning Wonderful Reports (Greek) This is the title of a text, correctly written it would read "περί θαυμάσιων ακουσμάτων" or Perí thaumásion akousmáton in the Latin alphabet</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
      </listAnnotation>
      <listBibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_200">
            <author>Lazzaro Spallanzani</author>
            <title level="j">Viaggi alle Due Sicilie e in alcune parti dell'Appennino</title>
            <date when="1797">1797</date>
            <biblScope unit="volume">6</biblScope>
         </bibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_225">
            <author>Dolomieu</author>
            <title level="j">Mémoire sur les îles Ponces</title>
            <date when="1783">1783</date>
            <biblScope unit="page">1–434</biblScope>
         </bibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_333">
            <author>William Hamilton</author>
            <title level="j">Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London</title>
            <title level="a" type="main">An account of the late eruption of Mount Vesuvius</title>
            <date when="1795">1795</date>
            <biblScope unit="volume">85</biblScope>
            <biblScope unit="page" from="73" to="116">73-116</biblScope>
         </bibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_334">
            <author>Heneage Finch</author>
            <author> 3rd earl of Winchilsea</author>
            <title level="a" type="main">A true and exact relation of the late prodigious earthquake &amp; eruption of Mount Aetna, or, Monte-Gibello ; as it came in a letter written to His Majesty from Naples by the Right Honorable the Earle of Winchilsea, His Majesties late ambassador at Constantinople, who in his return from thence, visiting Catania in the island of Sicily, was an ey-witness [sic] of that dreadfull spectacle.</title>
            <date when="1669">1669</date>
            <note>Originally a letter to King Charles II, Finch's description of Etna was immediately published as a pamphlet. </note>
         </bibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_328">
            <author>Robert Plot</author>
            <title level="j">Natural History of Oxfordshire</title>
            <date when="1677">1677</date>
         </bibl>
      </listBibl>
      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_397">
            <form>shale</form>
            <def>
               <p>Shale is a fine-grained, clastic sedimentary rock formed from mud that is a mix of flakes of clay minerals and tiny fragments of other minerals, especially quartz and calcite.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_090">
            <form>limestone</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sedimentary rock composed mainly of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_092">
            <form>granite</form>
            <def>
               <p>A coarse-grained intrusive igneous rock.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_482">
            <form>Pumice</form>
            <def>
               <p>a type of extrusive volcanic rock, produced when lava with a very high content of water and gases is discharged from a volcano.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_171">
            <form>sal ammoniac</form>
            <def>
               <p>A rare, naturally occurring mineral composed of ammonium chloride (NH4Cl). It forms colourless, white, or yellow-brown crystals.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_037">
            <form>sulphur</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: S</p>
               <p>Pure sulphur is a tasteless, odourless, brittle solid that is pale yellow in colour, a poor conductor of electricity, and insoluble in water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_013">
            <form>muriate of ammonia</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: NH4Cl</p>
               <p>An inorganic compound and a white crystalline salt that is highly soluble in water. Solutions of ammonium chloride are mildly acidic. In its naturally occurring mineralogic form, it is known as sal ammoniac.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_032">
            <form>pyrites</form>
            <def>
               <p>A generic term for sulphide minerals.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_175">
            <form>bitumen</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sticky, black, highly viscous liquid or semi-solid form of petroleum.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_058">
            <form>carbonic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CO2 or H2CO3 </p>
               <p>Now known as Carbon dioxide (CO2), or a solution of carbon dioxide in water (H2CO3). </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_105">
            <form>basalt</form>
            <def>
               <p>A dark grey to black dense to fine-grained igneous rock that consists of basic plagioclase, augite, and usually magnetite. More than 90% of volcanic rock on earth is basaltic.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_078">
            <form>elastic fluid</form>
            <def>
               <p>A descriptive term for a gas, emphasising its elastic quality of spontaneous expansion.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_503">
            <form>Aqueous vapour</form>
            <def>
               <p>Also known as water vapour; the gaseous phase of water which can be produced from the evaporation or boiling of water as a liquid, or from the sublimation of ice. Water vapour is invisible to the eye due to its gaseous form. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_254">
            <form>common air</form>
            <def>
               <p>The air of the lower stratum of the atmosphere, or the air that we breathe, which is a mixture of several gases, including oxygen (O2), nitrogen (N2) and carbon dioxide (CO2).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
   </standOff>
   <text>
      <body xml:lang="en">
         <div>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="1"
                xml:id="pb-1"
                facs="#i1"/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Volcanoes</hi>
            <lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#misc_694"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag1">
          By far the greatest changes
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
produced upon the solid<lb/>
parts of the surface of<lb/>
the Globe in late times,<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">have resulted</hi> from the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">agencies of volcanic fires.</hi>
            <lb/>
- the Causes &amp; the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects</hi> of Volcanoes are<lb/>
subjects which cannot<lb/>
fail to excite curiosity<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
in all minds attached to<lb/>
the knowledge of Nature:<lb/>
|_ And their importance in<lb/>
Geological Theory is great<lb/>
&amp; distinct; for they afford<lb/>
the only known facts<lb/>
of the agency <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Heat</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">upon rocks, which</hi> occur<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">on a great</hi> scale <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in</del>
            <lb/>
their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">relations</hi> to general<lb/>
Theory <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">are</hi> numerous &amp;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">interesting</hi>. -<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">- The objects belonging</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to this department</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of Science are very extensive</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
- |_ Amongst the Greek Historians<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#person_844"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="person">
          Thucidedes
        </name>
            </rs> mentions a great<lb/>
eruption of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="place">
                  <hi rend="underline">Etna</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> which<lb/>
took place 476 years before <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#person_951"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="person">
          Christ
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
but he gives no accurate<lb/>
details.<lb/>
Of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">philosophers</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Greek Naturalists</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag5" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>charged</unclear>
            </del>  in his trea <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#nonenglish_356"
                type="nonenglish">
               <term xml:id="tag6">
          περι ϑαυμαςιων ακ
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
=<rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#nonenglish_356"
                type="nonenglish">
               <term xml:id="tag7">
          ματων
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
or concerning wonderful reports<lb/>
states that he had heard of<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">that heated were</del> fires <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">that</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">which</add>
            <lb/>
burnt by night &amp; issued<lb/>
out of the earth in<lb/>
the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_1325"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          Eolian isles
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; He<lb/>
was perfectly well acquainted<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
with the Volcanoes of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#place_569"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag9" type="place">
          Sicily
        </name>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
- - The first eruption of<lb/>
Vesuvius certainly known to<lb/>
have taken place was in y<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">e</hi> 79 <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">year</add> after<lb/>
the Christian Era that eruption<lb/>
in which <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#person_185"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="person">
                  <add>the Elder</add> Pliny
        </name>
            </rs> lost his life<lb/>
but <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#person_448"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag11" type="person">
          Diodorus Siculus
        </name>
            </rs>; &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#person_510"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag12" type="person">
          Strabo
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
who <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">flourished in the time</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">were both born before the death</add>
            <lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#person_401"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
          Julius Cesar
        </name>
            </rs>, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">both</del> were<lb/>
of opinion that the mountain<lb/>
had burnt in remote ages<lb/>
|_ &amp; that this must have been<lb/>
the cause is evident from<lb/>
the circumstance of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag14" ref="#place_407" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag14" type="place">
          Pompeia
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag15" ref="#place_714" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag15" type="place">
          Herculaneum
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> cities which were<lb/>
destroyed in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">first recorded</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">eruption</hi> being principally built<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
of lava.<lb/>
- . The Ancient Philosophers<lb/>
seem to have paid very<lb/>
little attention to the<lb/>
Natural history of Volcanoes,<lb/>
. - And even amongst the<lb/>
moderns till within the<lb/>
last forty years it<lb/>
has been but little an<lb/>
an object of study. -<lb/>
- <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag16" ref="#person_699" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag16" type="person">
          Sir W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> Hamilton
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> was<lb/>
one of the first persons<lb/>
who endeavoured <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to direct</del>
            <lb/>
to direct the observation<lb/>
of Men of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Science to the</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">subject.</hi> - His <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">observations</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">remarks</add> upon<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#place_169"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag17" type="place">
          Vesuvius 
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#misc_790"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag18">
          published in the Ph: Tran.
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
are well known |_ &amp; his work<lb/>
on the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#place_183"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="place">
          Phlegrean fields
        </name>
            </rs> equally<lb/>
demonstrates the extent of his<lb/>
knowledge &amp; the refinement<lb/>
of his taste.<lb/>
- Since the period in which<lb/>
the first remarks of our celebrated<lb/>
countryman were made known to<lb/>
the world the path that<lb/>
He has marked out has<lb/>
been pursued by many Philosophical<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">observers</hi> -<lb/>
Since that time <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#person_308"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag20" type="person">
          Spallanzani
        </name>
            </rs> has<lb/>
given many valuable remarks, on Volcanoes<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in how</del> in his work entitled <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#otherwork_200"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag21">
            travels into
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#otherwork_200"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag22">
            the two Sicilies
        </bibl>
            </rs> - <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <hi rend="underline">
                  <rs xml:id="ttag23" ref="#person_820" type="person">
                     <name xml:id="tag23" type="person">
          Breslac
        </name>
                  </rs>
               </hi>
            </unclear> has added<lb/>
considerably to our geological knowledge<lb/>
of them by his observations on<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#place_1168"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag24" type="place">
          Campania
        </name>
            </rs> |_ &amp; Barber &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#person_300"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag25" type="person">
          Dolomieu
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
have both treated <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in the subject</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
with great acuteness the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
minerology of this <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">department</del>
            <lb/>
branch of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Philosophy</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Science</add> -<lb/>
And if the most instructive<lb/>
of the works upon the<lb/>
subject were to be selected<lb/>
it would perhaps be<lb/>
the treatise of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag26"
                ref="#person_300"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag26" type="person">
          Dolomieu
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#otherwork_225"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag27">
                  <hi rend="underline">sur les isles ponces</hi>
               </bibl>
            </rs> on the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag28" ref="#place_408" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag28" type="place">
          Lipari
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> islands -<lb/>
- In this publication, the<lb/>
most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minute observations</hi>
            <lb/>
may be found combined<lb/>
with <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the <hi rend="underline">most</hi>
            </add>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">enlarged</hi> views.<lb/>
And the Author has<lb/>
enlightened his philosophical<lb/>
{<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">researches</hi>} -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
by the assistance of the<lb/>
most refined methods of<lb/>
Chemistry. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
- |_ The forms of Volcanic Mountains<lb/>
are usually conical &amp; those<lb/>
Rocks which constitute their<lb/>
bases &amp; which have not<lb/>
been altered by fire, differ<lb/>
very much in their nature<lb/>
in different districts. -<lb/>
The strata that appear<lb/>
at the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">foot</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#place_169"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag29" type="place">
                  <hi rend="underline">Vesuvius</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
are principally <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <unclear>
                  <rs xml:id="ttag30" ref="#chemical_397" type="chemical">
                     <term xml:id="tag30">
          shale
          
        </term>
                  </rs>
               </unclear>
               <rs xml:id="ttag31" ref="#chemical_090" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag31">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
|_ The foundations of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag32"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag32" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
are said to be <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag33"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag33">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
&amp; porphyry: <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">And</hi> these<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">substances</hi> according to the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
reports of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
